## Required Skills and Tools

**Soldering Safety**

* Wear eye protection (goggles, glasses).

* Never touch a hot solder iron to yourself or anyone else.

* When not using the solder, place the solder iron in a solder holder to avoid fires and burn accidents. 

* Lower the power or turn off when soldering iron is not in use.

* Do not directly expose yourself or others to the solder fumes. Make sure there is an air current (fan e.g.) or fume extractor for the solder smoke.

3. Soldering for Beginners Procedure

   * Put two rows of male header pins into the breadboard with the long pins down and place the training board on top with the text facing up so that the short pins poke out of the training board where you want them![](images\required_skills_and_tools1.JPG)

     * Turn on the soldering iron and set temperature to suggested value (written on the control box). Wait until it reaches the set temperature.

     * Starting on one end of the row of pins, place the flat end of the tip of solder iron on the pin and pad so that it touches them both simultaneously, then bring solder wire to the junction. 

     ​​

     * Melt a small bead of solder and hold hot iron until the solder is ‘sucked’ into the pad.![](images\required_skills_and_tools2.JPG)

     * Quickly remove iron (be aware of time, since the board can get overheated).

     * Repeat with the pin on the opposite end and continue going back and forth until you finish the last pin somewhere in the middle. This allows the area around the soldered pins to cool off a little.

     * Practice this for several rows of pins

4. Advanced Soldering Skill: Soldering without help of a breadboard

   * As best you can, place the pins or header into the pcb board and place the board on the table with the longer end of the pins/header sitting at an angle to the table.

     * Apply the soldering iron to an end pad and pin allowing the iron to heat the pad/pin.

     * Place the soldering wire into the iron/pad/pin junction

     * Melt a small bead of solder into the pad and hold until the melted solder is ‘sucked’ into the pad/pin. 

     * Quickly remove iron. At this point the pins will probably be crooked with respect to the PCB board. 

     * With one hand, hold the PCB board and place a finger on the header on the opposite side and end of the newly soldered pin.

     * Apply the iron onto the soldered pin to re-melt the solder. This will allow you to align the header with your finger to make a 90 degree angle with the test board.

     * This single soldered pin will hold the entire row of pins or header in position allowing you to proceed as above with the rest of the pins\! Note: Make sure to apply enough pressure so the header makes full contact with the pcb board.

**Using the Multimeter**

1. Tools  
   1. Multimeter  
   2. Testing leads  
      1. Banana plugs/ Alligator clips/ Test hooks  
   3. Assembled and wired board  
      1. I.e. any connection you’d like to test  
2. Procedure  
   1. Grab a multimeter and connect leads to respective inputs.  
   2. Turn on multimeter to desired test function  
      1. For this procedure we will be using the continuity function (wave of curved lines)  
   3. Once on the continuity function, touch the two leads together.  
      1. If you hear a beeping noise it is functioning properly.  
   4. Touch the probes on each end of the connection.  
      1. If you hear a beep the connection is stable.
